04926nam a22009255i 9780520939332DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209393327 a10.1525/97805209393322doi  a(DE-B1597)519614  a(OCoLC)1114902718  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aTX 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a641.59721 aPinedo, Encarnación, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEncarnación’s Kitchen :bMexican Recipes from Nineteenth-Century California /cEncarnación Pinedo. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v90 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1991 Ruth Reichl, then a Los Angeles Times food writer, observed that much of the style now identified with California cuisine, and with nouvelle cuisine du Mexique, was practiced by Encarnación Pinedo a century earlier. A landmark of American cuisine first published in 1898 as El cocinero español (The Spanish Cook), Encarnación's Kitchen is the first cookbook written by a Hispanic in the United States, as well as the first recording of Californio food—Mexican cuisine prepared by the Spanish-speaking peoples born in California. Pinedo's cookbook offers a fascinating look into the kitchens of a long-ago culture that continues to exert its influence today. Of some three hundred of Pinedo's recipes included here—a mixture of Basque, Spanish, and Mexican—many are variations on traditional dishes, such as chilaquiles, chiles rellenos, and salsa (for which the cook provides fifteen versions). Whether describing how to prepare cod or ham and eggs (a typical Anglo dish labeled "huevos hipócritas"), Pinedo was imparting invaluable lessons in culinary history and Latino culture along with her piquant directions. In addition to his lively, clear translation, Dan Strehl offers a remarkable view of Pinedo's family history and of the material and literary culture of early California cooking. Prize-winning journalist Victor Valle puts Pinedo's work into the context of Hispanic women's testimonios of the nineteenth century, explaining how the book is a deliberate act of cultural transmission from a traditionally voiceless group.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCookingzCalifornia. 0aCooking, AmericanxCalifornia style. 0aCooking, Mexican. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  a19th century.  aamerican cuisine.  aamericana.  abasque recipes.  acalifornia cuisine.  acalifornia food.  acalifornia.  acook in the kitchen.  acookbooks.  acuisine.  aculinary history.  aencarnacion pinedo.  afood and culture.  afood lovers.  afood writing.  afood.  afoodies.  ahispanic influence.  ahistorical cookbooks.  ahome cooks.  amexican cuisine.  amexican food.  amexican recipes.  anonfiction.  apast cultures.  arecipe book.  aregional cuisine.  arestaurant settings.  aspanish recipes.  atraditional cooking.1 aStrehl, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValle, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093933240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939332423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939332/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alle